    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text
          padding="10px 12px"
          font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;"
          color="#000000"
        >
          <h2
            style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            "
          >
            Japanese election
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image
          border-radius="10px"
          padding="10px 12px"
          width="600px"
          src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/japan-election-2025-ruling-coalition-falls-short.jpg"
          alt="The ruling coalition needed 50 seats to retain control of the 248-seat upper chamber. It ended up with 47"
          href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com"
        />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i
              >The ruling coalition needed 50 seats to retain control of the
              248-seat upper chamber. It ended up with 47. Credits: NYT</i
            >
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Japanese PM Shigeru Ishiba’s coalition
            headed to the polls as control over half of the 248-seat upper
            chamber was at stake. They
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-jul-25-spotlight-h1-1-lost-their-majority?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >lost their majority</a
            >
            as people were frustrated over the rising expenses and the threat of
            US tariffs. Speaking after the results, Ishiba said that he solemnly
            accepts the harsh result, but intends to remain in position.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The background:</strong> The rise of the
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-jul-25-spotlight-h1-2-far-right-sanseito-party?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >far-right Sanseito party</a
            >
            and their “Japanese First” campaign has struck a chord with voters.
            They use anti-immigration propaganda, tax cut assertions, and
            conspiracy theories to sway public support. Ishiba’s coalition has
            failed to address the rising number of tourists and foreign
            immigrants, who are often found to disrespect Japan’s conservative
            ecosystem.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px)">
            <strong>The big picture:</strong> This loss follows their poor
            showing in the lower house
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-jul-25-spotlight-h1-3-election-in-october-2024?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >election in October 2024</a
            >. Analysts predict that the loss would result in a potential shift
            in leadership, potentially leading to political turmoil and economic
            instability. The
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-21-jul-25-spotlight-h1-4-yen-has-strengthened?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >yen has strengthened</a
            >
            on global markets as investors expected this result.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
